["Asthma is a chronic disease characterized by the occurrence of frequent attacks ranging from dyspnea to wheezing, and they differ in severity and frequency from one person to another.", "Its symptoms may appear several times a day or a week in individuals with it, and for some they become worse during physical activity or at night.", "During an asthma attack, the lining of the bronchial tubes swells, narrowing the airways and reducing the flow of air in and out of the lungs.", "Recurring asthma symptoms often cause insomnia, daytime fatigue, decreased activity levels, and absenteeism from school and work.", "Asthma mortality rates are relatively low compared to other chronic diseases.", "Asthma facts", "It is estimated that over 339 million people suffer from asthma (1).", "It is one of the most common noncommunicable diseases among children.", "But most of the deaths from it occur in adults.", "Asthma is a public health problem not only for high-income countries; It appears in all countries, regardless of their level of development.", "Most of its deaths occur in low- and lower-middle-income countries.", "Asthma diagnosis and treatment are not up to standard.", "It burdens individuals and families with a heavy burden, and often restricts individuals' activities for life.", "Causes of asthma", "The underlying causes of the disease are not fully understood.", "The strongest risk factors for infection are a set of genetic predispositions associated with exposure to inhalation of substances and particles that can provoke allergic reactions or irritate the respiratory tract, such as the following:", "Indoor allergens (such as house dust mites in upholstery, carpets, upholstered furniture, pollution, and pet dander).", "External allergens (such as pollen and mold)", "Tobacco smoke", "Chemical irritants in the workplace", "air pollution.", "Other triggers can include cold air, intense emotional stress such as anger or fear, and physical exercise.", "Certain medications can also irritate the disease, as follows: aspirin and other non-steroid and anti-inflammatory drugs, and beta-blockers (used to treat hypertension, heart disease and migraine).", "Urban expansion has been associated with an increased rate of asthma.", "But the exact nature of this relationship is not clear.", "Reducing the burden of asthma", "Although asthma cannot be cured, appropriate management can control the disease and enable people to enjoy a good quality of life.", "Medicines are used for a short time to relieve symptoms.", "Medicines such as inhaled steroids are needed for a long time to control the progression of severe asthma.", "People with persistent symptoms should take medication for a long period of time on a daily basis to control underlying inflammation and prevent symptoms and exacerbations.", "Insufficient access to medicines is an important reason for poor asthma control in many places.", "Medicines are not the only way to combat asthma.", "It is also important to avoid disease triggers - triggers that irritate and inflame the airways.", "And every patient with asthma should know, after being medically assisted, the triggers to avoid.", "Although asthma does not cause death the way chronic obstructive pulmonary diseases or other chronic diseases do, failure to use appropriate medications or adhere to treatment can kill the patient.", "WHO strategy for preventing and controlling asthma", "WHO recognizes that asthma is of major public health importance and plays a role in coordinating international efforts to combat it.", "The purpose of its strategy is to support Member States in their efforts to reduce disability and premature death resulting from it.", "The objectives of the WHO program are:", "Improving access to cost-effective interventions including medicines, raising standards and facilitating access to care at all levels of the health care system.", "Disease surveillance to draw a map showing the severity of asthma, analyze its determinants and monitor its trends, with a focus on the poor and disadvantaged population groups. And providing primary prevention of the disease to reduce exposure to common risk factors that cause infection, especially tobacco smoke, frequent cases of respiratory infection with less severity during childhood, and air pollution (and various internal, external and occupational factors).", "Global Alliance Against Chronic Respiratory Diseases", "The Global Alliance against Chronic Respiratory Diseases contributes to the organization\u2019s activities to prevent and control these diseases.", "It is a voluntary alliance that includes national and international organizations and agencies from many countries.", "The alliance focuses on the needs of low- and middle-income countries and vulnerable populations, and promotes initiatives specifically designed to meet local needs."]